`,o.jsx(n.h2,{children:"title: Whitepaper (Full Preview)"}),`
`,o.jsx(n.h1,{children:"Credit Markets for Time-Locked Digital Assets"}),`
`,o.jsx(n.h2,{children:"A Protocol for Borrowing Against Vested and Locked Tokens"}),`
`,o.jsxs(n.p,{children:["Version 2.0",o.jsx(n.br,{}),`
`,"Date: January 28, 2026",o.jsx(n.br,{}),`
`,"Authors: Protocol Genesis Team (Inspired by First-Principles Innovation)"]}),`
`,o.jsx(n.h3,{children:"Abstract"}),`
`,o.jsx(n.p,{children:"In the decentralized economy of Web3, tokenized incentives drive alignment and growth. Yet, vesting schedules and token lockups -- designed to prevent dumps and ensure commitment -- create a paradox: trillions in on-chain value remain economically inert. Holders own assets with real market price but zero immediate utility, often resorting to inefficient workarounds like deeply discounted OTC sales or premature liquidations that erode ecosystem trust."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.p,{children:"This whitepaper presents a decentralized protocol that resolves this inefficiency. Users can borrow against the discounted present value (DPV) of their time-locked tokens without transferring ownership, breaking vesting rules, or relying on off-chain enforcement. Key innovations include conservative risk modeling via mathematical discount curves, automated on-chain settlement at unlock time, and an optional identity-aware credit layer for persistent reputation. The protocol is non-custodial, composable, and governed by a DAO, establishing a new financial primitive for DAOs, startups, and contributors."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.p,{children:"Built on first-principles engineering -- like optimizing reusable rockets to reduce space travel costs -- this system unlocks liquidity while preserving long-term incentives. It bridges the gap between ownership and utility, potentially activating billions in trapped capital. No prior documents needed: This is your complete blueprint to understand, evaluate, and build upon."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.hr,{}),`
`,o.jsx(n.h2,{children:"1. Introduction"}),`
`,o.jsx(n.p,{children:"Decentralized networks and Web3 organizations rely on token-based compensation to align participants with sustained success. Vesting mechanisms -- where tokens unlock gradually over time -- and lockups -- fixed periods of non-transferability -- are standard tools to mitigate short-term speculation and promote longevity. These structures are effective: They bind founders, employees, contributors, and investors to the project's horizon."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.p,{children:"However, they impose a severe cost: Illiquidity. Token holders possess legally and programmatically owned assets with observable market value, yet they cannot access that value for months or years. This locks away economic potential, forcing individuals into suboptimal choices -- such as borrowing from centralized lenders with custodial risks or selling future claims at steep discounts via over-the-counter (OTC) deals."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.p,{children:"Traditional DeFi protocols like Aave or Compound excel at lending against liquid collateral but fail here: They require transferable assets that can be liquidated on price drops, not time-based claims. Off-chain solutions introduce counterparty risks, legal complexities, and regulatory hurdles. This whitepaper proposes a protocol that addresses these gaps head-on."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.p,{children:"Our approach: Enable borrowing against escrowed claim rights to future unlocks, valued conservatively through DPV models. Loans accrue interest and settle automatically via smart contracts at vesting expiry -- no courts, no custodians, just code. Optional integration with decentralized identities (DIDs) or DAO credentials builds cross-wallet credit histories, evolving beyond anonymous wallet roulette."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.p,{children:"This isn't an incremental tweak; it's a foundational primitive. Like Tesla's battery packs storing energy for on-demand use, this protocol stores future token value and deploys it responsibly today. By design, it respects vesting integrity, enforces outcomes on-chain, and scales across ecosystems."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.hr,{}),`
`,o.jsx(n.h2,{children:"2. Problem Statement"}),`
`,o.jsx(n.h3,{children:"2.1 The Illiquidity Paradox in Web3"}),`
`,o.jsx(n.p,{children:'Vested or locked tokens represent "paper wealth" with real constraints:'}),`
`,o.jsxs(n.ul,{children:[`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Ownership is clear: Tokens are programmatically assigned via smart contracts (e.g., OpenZeppelin vesting libraries) and legally recognized."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Value is observable: Market prices from oracles (e.g., Chainlink) reflect current worth."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Utility is zero: Non-transferable during lockup, preventing sales, pledges, or DeFi interactions."}),`
`]}),`
`,o.jsx(n.p,{children:"This inefficiency affects millions: DAO contributors (e.g., in Arbitrum or Optimism), startup employees in token-heavy comp packages, early investors in seed rounds, and grant recipients from ecosystems like Solana or Ethereum. Estimates suggest over $1-2 trillion in locked tokens across Web3, with billions vesting annually. Holders face opportunity costs -- unable to fund personal needs, invest elsewhere, or weather volatility -- often leading to premature ecosystem exits."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.h3,{children:"2.2 Limitations of Existing Systems"}),`
`,o.jsxs(n.ul,{children:[`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"DeFi lending protocols: Platforms like Aave, Compound, or MakerDAO require liquid, transferable collateral. They use price-based liquidation (e.g., via oracles triggering sales on undercollateralization), not time-based risks. Vested positions cannot be deposited without breaking locks."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Centralized loans: Services like Ledn or centralized crypto lenders offer loans against locked assets but demand custody, KYC, and jurisdiction-specific compliance. Enforcement relies on legal recourse, introducing opacity and single points of failure."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"OTC deals and secondary markets: Informal arrangements discount future claims by 30-70%, exposing parties to counterparty default and legal disputes. Platforms like SecondSwap enable trading but not borrowing, forcing sellers to forfeit upside."}),`
`]}),`
`,o.jsx(n.p,{children:"These solutions fragment liquidity, amplify risks, and undermine the decentralized ethos."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.hr,{}),`
`,o.jsx(n.h2,{children:"3. Competitor and Landscape Analysis"}),`
`,o.jsx(n.p,{children:'To validate novelty, we conducted exhaustive searches across web queries ("DeFi protocols for borrowing against vested locked tokens"), X (formerly Twitter) for real-time updates, and direct site browses. No protocol fully matches our design: on-chain borrowing against non-transferable vesting claims with DPV valuation, auto-settlement at unlock, and vesting-preserving enforcement. Adjacent projects exist but address subsets.'}),`
`,o.jsx(n.h3,{children:"SecondSwap"}),`
`,o.jsx(n.p,{children:"A decentralized exchange for trading locked/vested tokens without early unlocks."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.p,{children:"Recent developments (as of January 2026):"}),`
`,o.jsxs(n.ul,{children:[`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Raised $1.2M in seed funding (November 2024)."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Partnered with Magna and TokenOps for issuer-approved secondary liquidity (August/September 2025)."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Expanded to Avalanche and onboarded billions in inventory."}),`
`]}),`
`,o.jsxs(n.p,{children:["Strengths: Transparent markets preserve vesting; audited by Code4rena (February 2025 fixes for vesting transfers).",o.jsx(n.br,{}),`
`,"Weaknesses: Focuses on sales, not borrowing -- users take permanent haircuts, no yield retention.",o.jsx(n.br,{}),`
`,"Market traction: Targets $1.5-$2.5T locked token space but lacks credit primitives."]}),`
`,o.jsx(n.h3,{children:"Diffuse (zkServerless)"}),`
`,o.jsx(n.p,{children:'Enables locked/staked assets in restaking and lending via "collateral abstraction" (e.g., without unlocking).'}),`
`,o.jsx(n.p,{children:"Updates (2024-2026):"}),`
`,o.jsxs(n.ul,{children:[`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Emphasized zkMesh and lattice SNARKs (October 2025 X posts)."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Integrations with Symbiotic for cross-chain."}),`
`]}),`
`,o.jsxs(n.p,{children:["Strengths: Activates staked value in ecosystems.",o.jsx(n.br,{}),`
`,"Weaknesses: Geared toward liquid-staked derivatives (e.g., stETH), not pure vesting claims; no native DPV for time-locks or unlock-time settlement."]}),`
`,o.jsx(n.h3,{children:"Other DeFi Players"}),`
`,o.jsxs(n.ul,{children:[`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Aave/Compound/Maker: Liquid collateral only; recent v4 updates (e.g., Aave hooks) add cross-chain but ignore vesting."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Emerging: IO DeFi (yield contracts, November 2025), Radiant Capital (cross-chain lending), Liquity (stablecoin focus). None handle non-transferable time-locks natively."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Reputation-based: Maple Finance offers institutional undercollateralized loans but relies on off-chain credit checks."}),`
`]}),`
`,o.jsxs(n.p,{children:["Gaps: No protocol combines time-based risk pricing, automatic unlock enforcement, and optional identity for credit continuity.",o.jsx(n.br,{}),`
`,"Our moat: Conservative curves ensure lender safety; composability with existing vesting standards (e.g., Sablier, OpenZeppelin) enables rapid adoption."]}),`
`,o.jsx(n.hr,{}),`
`,o.jsx(n.h2,{children:"4. System Overview"}),`
`,o.jsx(n.p,{children:"The protocol allows users to escrow claim rights to vested/locked tokens, borrow stablecoins or other assets against their DPV, and repay over time. At unlock, smart contracts enforce settlement: release tokens on full repayment, partial seizure on underpayment, or full liquidation on default."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.p,{children:"Key characteristics:"}),`
`,o.jsxs(n.ul,{children:[`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Non-custodial: Users retain control; protocol escrows only claim rights (e.g., via NFTs wrapping vesting positions)."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"On-chain enforcement: No off-chain intervention -- settlement triggered by block timestamps."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Conservative risk modeling: DPV discounts front-load risks, capping loan-to-value (LTV) at 20-40%."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Optional identity-linked credit: Enhances terms without mandating disclosure."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Composable: Adapters for common vesting contracts; integrable with DAOs and frontends."}),`
`]}),`
`,o.jsx(n.h3,{children:"Optional Auction Primitive (Non-Loan Liquidity)"}),`
`,o.jsx(n.p,{children:"In addition to borrowing, the protocol can offer a separate auction mechanism where users sell their vested/locked claim rights at a market-clearing discount. This is a non-debt path for users who want immediate exit without repayment risk:"}),`
`,o.jsxs(n.ul,{children:[`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Asset sold: Claim rights (escrowed as NFTs), not the underlying tokens."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Auction types: Dutch (price decays), English (bids climb), and Sealed Bid (commit/reveal first-price). Future variants include Vickrey (second-price sealed bid) and Reverse (buyer-driven bids) as modular extensions."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Settlement: Winner receives the claim rights at unlock; seller receives stablecoins (minus fee)."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Safety: Protocol treasury can bid only at deep discounts (e.g., 50-80% off DPV), so it never lends or takes price risk."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Market impact: Early exits flow to long-term holders (including treasury), reducing unlock-day sell pressure."}),`
`]}),`
`,o.jsx(n.p,{children:"This creates value for:"}),`
`,o.jsxs(n.ul,{children:[`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Borrowers: Liquidity without selling upside."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Lenders: Yield from secured, predictable collateral."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"DAOs/startups: Retain talent by enabling financial flexibility."}),`
`]}),`
`,o.jsx(n.hr,{}),`
`,o.jsx(n.h2,{children:"5. Architecture"}),`
`,o.jsx(n.h3,{children:"5.1 Core Components"}),`
`,o.jsxs(n.ul,{children:[`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Vesting and lock adapters: Interface with external contracts (e.g., OpenZeppelin, Sablier) to verify schedules, escrow claims, and enforce non-transferability."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Valuation and risk engine: Computes DPV and borrow limits."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Lending pools: Manage liquidity supply, allocations, and yields."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Loan management contracts: Handle issuance, tracking, and settlement."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Auction module (optional): Runs time-based auctions for claim-right NFTs; settles to stablecoins with protocol fees."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Identity and reputation module (optional): Integrates DIDs, DAO credentials, or KYC for credit scoring."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Governance framework: DAO for parameters, risk committees for oversight."}),`
`]}),`
`,o.jsx(n.h3,{children:"5.2 Security and Integration"}),`
`,o.jsxs(n.ul,{children:[`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Audits: Multi-auditor (e.g., PeckShield, Quantstamp) for all contracts."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Oracles: Redundant (Chainlink, Pyth) for prices and volatility."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Chains: Ethereum mainnet MVP; multi-chain via LayerZero or CCIP."}),`
`]}),`
`,o.jsx(n.hr,{}),`
`,o.jsx(n.h2,{children:"6. Collateral Valuation"}),`
`,o.jsx(n.p,{children:"Locked tokens are illiquid futures, so we value them via discounted present value (DPV):"}),`
`,o.jsx(n.p,{children:"PV = Q * P * D"}),`
`,o.jsx(n.p,{children:"Where:"}),`
`,o.jsxs(n.ul,{children:[`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Q: Token quantity."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"P: Current market price (oracle-fed)."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"D: Composite discount factor (0-1)."}),`
`]}),`
`,o.jsx(n.h3,{children:"Discount Factors"}),`
`,o.jsxs(n.ul,{children:[`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Time to unlock: Exponential decay, D_time = e^(-r t) (r = risk-free rate, t = time in years)."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Volatility: Simplified sqrt-time adjustment, D_vol = 1 - sigma * sqrt(t) (sigma = volatility)."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Liquidity depth: Adjusts for market slippage (e.g., 0.9 for deep markets)."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Unlock supply impact: Discounts for dilution shocks (e.g., 0.95)."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Protocol risk: Token-specific score (e.g., governance stability)."}),`
`]}),`
`,o.jsx(n.p,{children:"LTV: Capped dynamically (20-40%), governed by DAO."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.h3,{children:"Expanded Risk Curve Simulations (Deterministic)"}),`
`,o.jsx(n.p,{children:"Assumptions retained and refined:"}),`
`,o.jsxs(n.ul,{children:[`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Risk-free rate r = 5% (annual)."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Liquidity factor = 0.9."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Shock factor = 0.95."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Q = 1000 tokens, P = 10 (for borrow limit examples)."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"LTV decreases linearly from 40% at t = 0 to a 25% floor at t = 36 months."}),`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"Time is in months, t_years = t / 12."}),`
`]}),`
`,o.jsx(n.p,{children:"Formulas:"}),`
`,o.jsxs(n.ul,{children:[`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"D_time = e^(-r * t_years)"}),`
`,o.jsx(n.li,{children:"D_vol = max(1 - sigma * sqrt(t_years), 0)"}),`
